\begin{abstract}
Material procurement is a core operational function of heavy industry enterprises such as the Vinacomin Mining Chemical Industry Holding Corporation (MICCO), where decision-making processes depend on the integration of technical, operational, and business information. In practice, MICCO’s data environment is characterized by fragmentation across heterogeneous information systems, semantic inconsistency between datasets, and the lack of explicit semantic relationships among entities. Although technical metadata is available, it is insufficient to represent business context, process semantics, and organizational knowledge structures, resulting in isolated data repositories rather than an integrated enterprise knowledge space.

This study proposes an integrated framework combining Enterprise Knowledge Graph–based GraphRAG and AI Agent architectures to support semantic search, knowledge integration, and organizational data governance. A domain knowledge structure for MICCO’s material procurement activities is developed, distinguishing explicit operational knowledge from tacit organizational knowledge and formalizing concepts, entities, and relations through ontological modeling. The proposed three-phase methodology—Knowledge Capture, Implementation, and Access—enables structured knowledge representation, semantic integration across heterogeneous systems, and reasoning-based access mechanisms. This approach supports complex inference tasks and provides a unified semantic layer that transforms fragmented enterprise data into an integrated organizational knowledge infrastructure.
\keywords{Enterprise Knowledge Graph \and MICCO \and Material Procurement \and Ontology \and Knowledge Management \and RAG Architecture \and AI Agent.}
\end{abstract}

