\paragraph{Context and Strategic Importance}: In heavy industry and mining support operations, material resource management directly affects the production stability, system safety, and regulatory compliance. At Vinacomin Mining Chemical Industry Holding Corporation (MICCO), a subsidiary of the Vietnam National Coal–Mineral Industries Group (TKV), material procurement spans a heterogeneous supply network that includes chemical inputs, industrial equipment, and specialized heavy machinery, each governed by different safety, storage, and handling constraints.

Unlike conventional inventory systems, MICCO’s material management processes are constrained by National Technical Regulations (QCVN), internal safety protocols, and sector-specific compliance procedures. As a result, operational effectiveness depends not only on data availability but on the ability to systematically organize, interlink, and interpret material information across regulatory, technical, and operational dimensions. The integration of these heterogeneous information layers therefore becomes a strategic requirement for risk control, operational reliability, and decision support within the organization.
\paragraph{The Challenge: Semantic Complexity and the Metadata Gap} 
Despite the availability of large volumes of digital records, large enterprises such as Vinacomin Mining Chemical Industry Holding Corporation (MICCO) face structural difficulties in organizing and interpreting enterprise data. Information is distributed across heterogeneous systems, including transactional data in ERP platforms, planning and reporting data in spreadsheets, and technical documentation in unstructured formats such as PDF files. These data sources are developed for different operational purposes and follow incompatible data models and semantics.

Although technical metadata (e.g., database schemas, file attributes, system-level descriptors) is generally available, it does not encode business rules, process semantics, regulatory constraints, or domain-specific relationships. As a result, enterprise information systems can record transactional facts (e.g., what materials were procured and from which suppliers), but they cannot represent decision rationales, safety dependencies, or regulatory linkages, such as the relationships between materials, geological safety standards, and operational risk requirements, without extensive manual modeling. This structural limitation creates a persistent semantic gap between data representations and organizational knowledge, leaving critical knowledge assets distributed across isolated information systems rather than integrated into a coherent enterprise knowledge structure.
\paragraph{Limitations of Traditional RAG Approaches} In enterprise information systems, Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) solutions are commonly implemented on top of vector databases that support embedding-based similarity search. While this architecture is effective for document retrieval tasks, it exhibits structural limitations when applied to enterprise knowledge environments. Vector-based retrieval mechanisms operate on local semantic similarity and treat documents as independent text fragments, which leads to the retrieval of contextually disconnected segments rather than semantically integrated knowledge units.

This retrieval paradigm does not encode explicit relationships, hierarchical dependencies, or process structures that characterize enterprise data. Consequently, queries that require multi-entity reasoning, dependency tracing, or cross-system integration cannot be reliably resolved through vector similarity alone. For example, answering a multi-hop query such as identifying suppliers associated with safety incidents in underground mining operations requires the integration of procurement records, safety incident reports, regulatory compliance documents, and project specifications within a unified relational model. Without explicit relational representations and reasoning mechanisms, traditional RAG pipelines lack the structural capacity to support such inference tasks.
\paragraph{The Solution: Synergizing GraphRAG and AI Agents}: To address the structural limitations of vector-based RAG systems, this study proposes an integrated framework that combines GraphRAG—based on Enterprise Knowledge Graph (EKG) representations—with AI Agent–based orchestration mechanisms. The core design principle is the explicit grounding of generative models in a structured knowledge representation layer, enabling retrieval and reasoning processes to operate over semantically defined entities and relations rather than isolated text fragments.
\begin{itemize}
    
\item GraphRAG Component: The Enterprise Knowledge Graph provides a formal representation of organizational knowledge, in which entities (e.g., suppliers, materials, safety standards) and their relationships are explicitly modeled. Retrieval operations are therefore performed through relational traversal (e.g., Supplier → Material → Safety Standard) instead of similarity-based matching alone, enabling context-aware access to information and semantically coherent response generation.
\item AI Agents Component: The framework incorporates AI Agents responsible for workflow orchestration and task coordination. These agents manage query decomposition, determine appropriate retrieval strategies (graph-based retrieval versus vector-based retrieval), and execute reasoning procedures across heterogeneous knowledge sources. This architecture supports multi-step reasoning, cross-domain integration, and structured response construction.

\end{itemize}
\paragraph{Contributions of this Paper} This study presents a complete methodology for constructing the Material Enterprise Knowledge Graph and implementing the hybrid GraphRAG–Agent framework for Vinacomin Mining Chemical Industry Holding Corporation (MICCO). The main contributions include: 
\begin{itemize}
\item the development of a domain-specific ontology for material procurement;
\item a data ingestion and structured pipeline for heterogeneous sources (including OCR and NLP processing); and
\item the design of an agent-based RAG architecture that supports knowledge integration, governance mechanisms, and enterprise search functions, enabling the transformation of distributed organizational data into an integrated operational knowledge infrastructure.
\end{itemize}

\section{Literature Review}

Knowledge Graphs (KGs) provide a formal framework for structured knowledge representation based on graph models in which entities are represented as nodes and semantic relations as labeled edges. This representation enables the explicit encoding of domain concepts, relationships, and constraints, supporting reasoning, integration, and query operations over heterogeneous data sources.

Recent surveys, including the review by Kejriwal \cite{kejriwal2022knowledge}, 
%citation needed
document the expansion of knowledge graph research and its methodological diversification over the past decade, particularly in areas such as semantic search, question answering, and structured information retrieval. These developments reflect the increasing role of graph-based knowledge representations as a core infrastructure for building semantically grounded intelligent information systems rather than as standalone data integration tools \cite{abu2021domain}.

Modern knowledge management systems increasingly adopt semantic technologies to support structured representation, integration, and reasoning over organizational data. Mohammad et al. (2025) \cite{mohammad2025knowledge} conducted a systematic review of 73 studies examining the integration of Knowledge Graphs (KGs), RDF, and SPARQL in business management contexts. Their analysis shows that semantic technologies improve knowledge management capabilities by enabling context-aware retrieval and semantic disambiguation mechanisms rather than keyword-based search alone.

Similarly, Macedo et al. (2023)\cite{macedo2023knowledge} identify Knowledge Graphs as a core structural asset in organizational knowledge systems, emphasizing their role in supporting integrated data representations and decision-support processes. From an architectural perspective, Galkin et al. \cite{galkin2017enterprise} analyze alternative Enterprise Knowledge Graph (EKG) integration strategies, distinguishing between consolidated (“unified”) and virtualized (“federated”) architectures and identifying trade-offs in scalability, consistency, and governance. Their work positions EKGs as a structural integration layer for enterprise knowledge rather than as a standalone data repository.

The applicability of EKG architectures extends to domains requiring complex reasoning and high reliability. In the financial sector, Atzeni et al. (2020)\cite{atzeni2020weaving} developed the “Vada-Link” framework for the Central Bank of Italy, combining property graph models with logic-based reasoning to support recursive inference tasks such as company control and asset eligibility analysis. In the logistics and safety domain, Zhang et al. (2019) \cite{zhang2019construction} addressed fragmented regulatory knowledge in Maritime Dangerous Goods transport by constructing a domain-specific knowledge graph (KGMDG) that integrates safety regulations (e.g., IMDG Code) with chemical attributes. Their use of Semantic Web Rule Language (SWRL) enables formal reasoning over segregation and safety constraints.

These studies provide methodological and architectural foundations for applying Enterprise Knowledge Graphs to MICCO’s material procurement and safety compliance context, particularly for tasks requiring semantic integration, regulatory reasoning, and cross-domain knowledge linkage.


Recent research increasingly explores the integration of symbolic knowledge representations and data-driven generative models within neuro-symbolic AI frameworks. Dehal et al. (2025) \cite{dehal2025knowledge} analyze the complementary roles of Knowledge Graphs (KGs) and Large Language Models (LLMs), showing that KGs provide structured grounding mechanisms that reduce hallucination risks, while LLMs support natural language interfaces for accessing graph-based knowledge representations.

To address the high manual cost of Enterprise Knowledge Graph (EKG) construction, Sun et al. (2025) \cite{sun2025docs2kg} propose the “Docs2KG” framework, which applies human–LLM collaboration to extract structured knowledge from heterogeneous document collections, enabling scalable ingestion of unstructured enterprise data into unified graph representations.

In parallel, research is converging toward agent-oriented retrieval and reasoning architectures. Belleguie (2025)\cite{belleguie2025graphrag} introduces a GraphRAG framework that integrates LLM-based AI agents with enterprise knowledge graphs, demonstrating improved performance over conventional RAG pipelines in tasks such as querying, classification, and enterprise data discovery. Similarly, Buehler (2025) \cite{buehler2025agentic} proposes the concept of “Agentic Deep Graph Reasoning,” in which autonomous agents operate over graph-based knowledge structures to support self-organizing reasoning processes and distributed knowledge integration.

Together, these studies define an emerging research direction in which graph-based knowledge representations, generative models, and agent architectures are combined to support scalable reasoning, semantic integration, and intelligent enterprise knowledge management.
