\subsection{Enterprise Knowledge Graph Construction}
To address data fragmentation and semantic inconsistency, we construct an Enterprise Knowledge Graph (EKG) as a unified semantic infrastructure for organizational knowledge representation. The EKG is formally modeled as a semantic network graph $G=<C,E,R>$, where:
\begin{itemize}
\item C (Concepts): Represents the ontological schema (classes) defined via Web Ontology Language (OWL). This conceptual layer acts as the "skeleton," defining abstract business entities and their permissible interactions.
\item E (Entities): Represents the instance layer, populated by extracting real-world data from heterogeneous sources (structured databases, semi-structured logs, and unstructured documents).
\item R (Relations): Represents the semantic edges connecting entities (e.g., relates\_to, depends\_on), allowing the system to perform multi-hop traversal and discover hidden connections not explicitly stated in the raw data.
\end{itemize}
This structure unifies previously isolated data silos into a coherent semantic graph, enabling efficient traversal and consistency validation using SHACL constraints.
\subsection{Agentic Framework}
Unlike linear RAG pipelines that rely on single-query retrieval, the proposed framework adopts a Multi-Agent System (MAS) architecture to support complex reasoning processes. Inspired by the Mixture-of-Experts paradigm, the system is organized around a central orchestration component that coordinates multiple specialized agents which illustrated in Figure \ref{fig:AgentFramework}:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Router Agent (The Controller): This component performs query intent analysis and classifies user requests to determine the appropriate retrieval and reasoning strategy (e.g., direct factual retrieval or multi-step reasoning workflows), subsequently dispatching tasks to the corresponding agents.
\item Retrieval Agent (The Researcher): This agent interacts with the data layer using a hybrid retrieval strategy that integrates:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Vector Search: Vector-based retrieval, to capture semantic similarity in unstructured text corpora stored in vector databases (e.g., Milvus);
    \item Graph Traversal: Graph-based traversal, to exploit explicit relationships and hierarchical structures within the Enterprise Knowledge Graph (EKG) stored in graph databases (e.g., Neo4j), enabling context-aware entity retrieval.
    \end{itemize}
\item Reasoning Agent (The Analyst): This agent integrates structured and unstructured results, performs cross-source validation, and synthesizes the final response, ensuring that all outputs are explicitly grounded in retrieved evidence.
\end{enumerate}
