\section{Case Study: Application in Material Procurement at MICCO}
To validate the proposed Agentic GraphRAG framework, we apply it to the material procurement domain of MICCO, which is characterized by complex operational processes, strict safety regulations, and heterogeneous data sources.
\subsection{Business Context and Challenges}
MICCO operates a multi-stage supply chain covering the production and trading of industrial explosives (VLNCN) and mining chemicals. The material management process consists of eight core stages, ranging from demand planning to liquidation. A key challenge is the fragmentation of organizational data across multiple systems and formats:
\begin{itemize}
    \item 

Structured data: Inventory records and transaction histories stored in enterprise systems (ERP, Biportal, SQL Server);
\item 
Unstructured data: Safety regulations (QCVN), technical documentation (e.g., blasting passports), and supplier contracts stored as PDF or scanned documents;
\item 
Experiential knowledge: Operational practices and incident-handling procedures held by domain experts.
\end{itemize}
Answering complex operational queries, such as identifying suppliers associated with non-compliant emulsion explosives and the applicable regulatory constraints in a given period, requires integrating procurement records, quality inspection logs, and regulatory documents—capabilities that exceed the limits of traditional keyword-based retrieval and conventional RAG pipelines.

\subsection{Building the Material Knowledge Graph (M-EKG)}
We constructed the M-EKG to serve as the semantic backbone for the system.
\paragraph{Ontology Modeling} Using the Web Ontology Language (OWL), we defined a domain-specific ontology centered around seventeen core concepts ($\mathcal{C}$): \textit{Material} (VatTu), \textit{Supplier} (NhaCungCap), \textit{Contract} (HopDong), \textit{Warehouse} (Kho), \textit{Regulation} (QuyDinh), \textit{Incident} (SuCo), \textit{Purchase Order} (DonHang), \textit{Procurement Plan} (KeHoachMuaSam), \textit{Quotation} (ChaoGia), \textit{Receipt Note} (PhieuNhapKho), \textit{Delivery Note} (PhieuXuatKho), \textit{Construction Site} (CongTruong), \textit{Inspector} (NguoiKiemTra), \textit{Certificate} (ChungChi), \textit{Material Category} (DanhMucVatTu), \textit{Manufacturer} (NhaSanXuat), and \textit{Risk} (RuiRo). The ontology encompasses 38 semantic relations ($\mathcal{R}$) categorized into six functional groups. Key semantic relations include:

\textbf{Procurement Chain:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item (:DonHang) -[BAO\_GOM]$\rightarrow$ (:VatTu)
    \item (:NhaCungCap) -[CUNG\_CAP]$\rightarrow$ (:VatTu)
    \item (:ChaoGia) -[TU\_NHA\_CUNG\_CAP]$\rightarrow$ (:NhaCungCap)
    \item (:HopDong) -[DUOC\_LAP\_TU]$\rightarrow$ (:ChaoGia)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Storage \& Logistics:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item (:PhieuNhapKho) -[NHAP\_VAT\_TU]$\rightarrow$ (:VatTu)
    \item (:PhieuXuatKho) -[XUAT\_DEN]$\rightarrow$ (:CongTruong)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Quality \& Compliance:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item (:VatTu) -[TUAN\_THU\_THEO]$\rightarrow$ (:QuyDinh)
    \item (:VatTu) -[CO\_CHUNG\_CHI]$\rightarrow$ (:ChungChi)
    \item (:PhieuKiemTra) -[KIEM\_TRA]$\rightarrow$ (:VatTu)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Risk \& Incident Management:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item (:SuCo) -[LIEN\_QUAN\_DEN]$\rightarrow$ (:VatTu)
    \item (:SuCo) -[LIEN\_QUAN]$\rightarrow$ (:NhaCungCap)
    \item (:RuiRo) -[LIEN\_QUAN\_VAT\_TU]$\rightarrow$ (:VatTu)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Traceability:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item (:VatTu) -[NGUON\_GOC]$\rightarrow$ (:NhaCungCap)
    \item (:VatTu) -[SAN\_XUAT\_BOI]$\rightarrow$ (:NhaSanXuat)
    \item (:HopDong) -[GIAO\_HANG]$\rightarrow$ (:PhieuNhapKho)
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Data Ingestion Pipeline} We implemented a dual-path ingestion pipeline to populate the graph ($\mathcal{E}$):
\begin{itemize}
    \item  Structured Path: We used R2RML to map relational data from the ERP system (e.g., table DIM\_VATTU) directly to graph nodes (e.g., micco:Material), assigning unique URIs based on material codes.
\item Unstructured Path: For scanned documents like the "Blue Books" and QCVN standards, we utilized an OCR engine (Tesseract/PaddleOCR) fine-tuned for Vietnamese technical terms. The extracted text was chunked and embedded into a Vector Database (Milvus), while metadata (Date, Author) was linked to the corresponding nodes in the Graph Database (Neo4j).
\end{itemize}
\subsection{Agentic Workflow Design}
Instead of a monolithic processing chain, we deployed a system of specialized AI Agents orchestrated by LangGraph to handle complex procurement queries. The workflow comprises three distinct agents:
\paragraph{The Router Agent (Intent Classifier)} This is the entry point. It uses a Local LLM (Llama 3) to analyze the user's natural language query and classify it into specific intents:
\begin{itemize}
    
\item Fact Retrieval: E.g., "What is the inventory level of Ammonium Nitrate?" → Routes to Database Agent.
\item Compliance Check: E.g., "Does the current storage of detonators meet QCVN 01:2019?" → Routes to Retrieval Agent.
\item Complex Reasoning: E.g., "Analyze the correlation between Supplier A's materials and recent blasting failures." → Routes to the Multi-hop Reasoning Agent.
\paragraph{The Retrieval Agent (Hybrid Search)} This agent possesses two "tools" for information gathering:
\begin{itemize}
    
\item  Vector Tool: Queries Milvus to find semantically similar text chunks from safety regulations and contracts.
\item Graph Tool: Executes Cypher queries against Neo4j to traverse structural relationships (e.g., finding all Incidents connected to a specific Supplier via Material nodes). This hybrid approach ensures that both the content (text) and the context (relationships) are retrieved.
\end{itemize}
\paragraph{The Reasoner Agent (Analyst)} Acting as the final synthesizer, this agent receives the structured data from the Graph and unstructured context from the Vector DB. It utilizes the LLM to generate a coherent answer. Crucially, the agent is configured with a "Citation Constraint", requiring it to strictly reference the source documents (e.g., "According to Contract 123..." or "Based on Incident Report 456...") to ensure trustworthiness and mitigate hallucinations.
\paragraph{Deployment Environment} To ensure data sovereignty and security for sensitive mining data, the entire agent system, including the LLM and databases, is deployed On-Premise within MICCO’s private cloud infrastructure, utilizing Docker containers for scalability.
