\section{Results and Discussion}
In MICCO’s regulated material procurement environment, conventional retrieval systems are unable to resolve complex queries due to the fragmentation of knowledge across structured transactional systems (e.g., ERP) and unstructured compliance documentation (e.g., scanned PDFs). As a result, operational decision-making often requires queries that jointly access and integrate both data modalities. Representative examples include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Supplier Evaluation: Identifying suppliers offering 'Emulsion Explosives' below the 2024 ceiling price (Structured) AND holding a valid ISO 9001:2015 certificate from scanned dossiers (Unstructured).
\item Safety Auditing: Finding warehouses storing 'Delay Detonators' with an expiration date of over 6 months (Structured) AND verifying if their physical layouts comply with QCVN 01:2019/BCT safety distance regulations (Unstructured).
\end{itemize}
Such multi-hop queries exceed the capabilities of standalone retrieval systems, motivating the adoption of the proposed Agentic GraphRAG architecture to support intent routing, multimodal data access, and integrated reasoning. To evaluate the framework, the system was tested using the Hybrid Competency Queries defined in the business context. The evaluation focuses on the ability of the multi-agent workflow to coordinate graph traversal and semantic retrieval processes in order to produce consistent and explainable responses for MICCO’s material procurement operations.
\subsection{Agentic Workflow Execution and Graph Retrieval}
When a user submits a complex query, the workflow is initiated by the Router Agent, which classifies the intent and delegates tasks. The core of the knowledge discovery relies on the Retrieval Agent (Search Agent), which interacts directly with the Knowledge Graph (Neo4j) via Cypher queries and the Vector Database via semantic search.
