\paragraph{Comparative Analysis with Baseline Models}
To evaluate the effectiveness of our proposed, we compared its performance to four established baseline systems: (1) Traditional Search (TrdSer) (SQL Database + Keyword Search), (2) Standard RAG (StdRAG) (LLM + Vector Database), (3) Knowledge Graph QA (KGQA) (pure graph traversal without generative AI), and (4) Standard GraphRAG (StdGraRAG) (a linear pipeline combining Graph and Vector data without agentic routing). 
We use a benchmark dataset consisting of 40 evaluation questions grouped into three categories:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Simple queries (single-question, single-source, clearly defined answers);
\item Multi-hop reasoning queries (requiring inference across two or more entities or linked data tables);
\item Hybrid queries (integrating structured data sources (SQL/Graph) with unstructured data (technical documents and regulations)).
\end{itemize}
To evaluate system performance, four evaluation metrics are defined as follows:
METRIC 1: Hybrid Query Resolution\\
\textbf{Definition:} Measures the system’s ability to correctly answer queries requiring joint reasoning over structured and unstructured data.\\
\textbf{Evaluation:}
Exact Match (EM): Exact match with ground truth.
Token-level F1: Token overlap between output and reference.
Answer Accuracy (ACC): Binary correctness (Correct/Incorrect).
Primary metric: F1-score (balances precision and recall for variable-length answers).
Hybrid Query (Q3) correctness criteria:
An answer is considered correct iff it satisfies both:
(a) quantitative values are exact (EM for numerical data), and
(b) semantic explanation of regulations is valid (F1 ≥ 0.70).\\
METRIC 2: Explainability and Traceability\\
\textbf{Definition:} Measures the system’s ability to provide precise and verifiable sources for generated answers.\\
\textbf{Evaluation:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Citation Precision (CP):} Proportion of provided citations that are correct and independently verifiable.
    \[
        CP = \frac{|\text{Valid citations}|}{|\text{Total citations}|}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Citation Recall (CR):} Proportion of required ground-truth sources that are correctly cited.
    \[
        CR = \frac{|\text{Valid citations}|}{|\text{Required GT sources}|}
    \]

    \item \textbf{Source Coverage Score (SCS):} F1-score of CP and CR.

    \item \textbf{Granularity Level (GL):} Citation detail level:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item L0: No citation
        \item L1: Document/table name only
        \item L2: Document + page / table + filter condition
        \item L3: Specific Node ID / Record ID + graph relation path
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
METRIC 3: Hallucination Rate
\textbf{Definition:} Measures the proportion of answers containing unsupported or unverifiable information not grounded in the retrieved sources.\\
\textbf{Evaluation:}
RAGAS Faithfulness Score (automatic): 
    The RAGAS framework is used to measure the proportion of statements in the generated answer that can be logically inferred from the retrieved context.
    \[
        \text{Hallucination Rate} = 1 - \text{Faithfulness Score}
    \]
METRIC 4: Latency\\
\textbf{Definition:} Measures the computational efficiency of each architecture in terms of end-to-end response time from query submission to complete answer generation.\\
\textbf{Evaluation:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Average Latency (AL): Mean response time (in seconds) over 40 evaluation queries.
\end{itemize}
