The experimental results indicate a clear trade-off between reasoning quality and real-time performance. The strongest methods A5 dominate in hybrid query accuracy, explainability, and hallucination control—particularly for complex multi-step queries. While the iterative reasoning process introduces additional computational overhead, the resulting latency represents a manageable trade-off for applications that prioritize decision quality, robustness, and reasoning depth over strict real-time response, making A5 suitable for high-stakes analytical and decision-support scenarios.
\section{Conclusions}
This study presents an Agentic GraphRAG framework for managing complex material procurement data at MICCO through the integration of Enterprise Knowledge Graphs (EKGs) and a multi-agent architecture. The proposed approach addresses key limitations of conventional vector-based RAG by enabling structured reasoning and coordinated access to heterogeneous data sources.

The framework supports improved information retrieval, semantic interpretability, and governance by linking database structures to domain concepts and enabling traceable, evidence-grounded responses that are aligned with safety and regulatory requirements in the mining sector. In addition, the integration of semantic text retrieval with graph-based relational reasoning enables the resolution of multi-hop queries that cannot be effectively handled by standalone retrieval systems.

Overall, the proposed architecture provides a unified semantic framework for integrating fragmented enterprise data and supports more reliable information access and decision support in MICCO’s material procurement operations.
